1. Release 3 is still too large because JobItem + Parcels + TaskLog + PackingOverride + DualWrite are all being changed in one deployment.

2. jobWorkflow.js is still the single highest-risk component because 200+ embedded JSON access patterns must eventually be rewritten and can cause silent business logic regressions.

3. responseAdapters.js becomes a long-term technical debt layer because it permanently emulates old Mongo object shapes instead of forcing proper relational consumption.

4. prismaMongooseCompat.js still creates ORM abstraction mismatch because Prisma behavior and Mongoose behavior are fundamentally different and edge cases will keep appearing.

5. Dual-write architecture still accepts unavoidable temporary inconsistency because Mongo writes can succeed while PostgreSQL writes fail before SyncFailureWorker catches up.

6. SyncFailureQueue lacks full stack trace/error metadata which will make production debugging of Prisma failures harder during replay.

7. syncVersion based conflict detection is weak because Mongo __v does not guarantee correct ordering under concurrent updates across services.

8. WriteSyncLog.sourceHash conflict detection is underspecified because hashing strategy is not defined and inconsistent hashing can create false sync states.

9. CustomerPhone and CustomerEmail normalization increases write complexity for a low-value gain because simple array storage was already operationally sufficient.

10. Soft-delete Prisma middleware on $allOperations is risky because automatic query mutation can create hard-to-debug hidden filtering behavior.

11. findUnique interception in soft-delete middleware can break Prisma semantics because unique lookups may unexpectedly return null when records are soft deleted.

12. JobCard Release 2 still partially over-normalizes operational data because JobCard is almost always read as a single unit and decomposition adds unnecessary query complexity.

13. JobItemProcess.processVariant remains weakly typed because it is still String and can allow invalid uncontrolled values like GLOSSY/MATTE typo variants.

14. JobItemProcessDetail is too generic because multiple unrelated process structures are forced into one table causing sparse columns and schema ambiguity.

15. ProcessDetailType enum is under-modeled because DIE_CUTTING_ROW, CUTTING_SIZE, and CORNER_FLAG have fundamentally different data structures.

16. JobItem decomposition creates extremely heavy joins for dashboard queries and may perform worse than current JSONB querying under production load.

17. Benchmarking only before Release 3 is insufficient because performance regression must be continuously measured after every release.

18. DualWriteBase writes Mongo first without rollback strategy so MongoDB remains source of truth and PostgreSQL can silently lag behind.

19. SyncFailureWorker re-reading current Mongo state can still miss intermediate states if multiple rapid updates happen before retry execution.

20. Queue subsystem postponed to Release 5 creates architecture inconsistency because half the system becomes relational while queue still depends on legacy JSON design.

21. Keeping QueueSession pinnedJobs and pausedJobs as JSON until Release 5 means queueEngine.js must later undergo another risky hot-path rewrite.

22. Mongo read-only fallback after DB_MODE=postgres introduces operational complexity because both database infrastructures must still stay online.

23. DB_FALLBACK=mongo-readonly can hide PostgreSQL production bugs because the system may silently fallback instead of forcing immediate failure visibility.

24. Migration scripts depending on WriteSyncLog for idempotency can fail if partial writes happen before transaction boundaries are reached.

25. Per-job transaction migration in Release 3 may become very slow when migrating large production datasets with deeply nested item/process structures.

26. API compatibility adapters preserve old response shapes which delays proper refactoring and increases future maintenance burden.

27. Existing frontend remains tightly coupled to Mongo-style nested object structure and no progressive frontend normalization strategy exists.

28. No clear rollback strategy exists if Release 4 partially refactors jobWorkflow.js and business workflow logic starts failing mid-production.

29. Too much reliance on Prisma include trees can create memory-heavy large object graphs when loading Jobs with Items + Processes + Parcels simultaneously.

30. Entire architecture still underestimates total testing effort because every workflow module (Prepress, Press, Postpress, Dispatch, Billing, Queue, Reports) depends on these schema changes.